threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: PE32+ executable (console) x86-64, for MS Windows

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample exhibits several high-confidence indicators of malicious behavior typical of a loader or backdoor. Key behaviors include: 1) Evasion: Manual traversal of the Process Environment Block (PEB) and Loader data structures in sub_140001170 to locate kernel32.dll and GetProcAddress, bypassing static Import Address Table (IAT) analysis. 2) Obfuscation: Extensive use of XOR and NOT-based decryption loops to hide strings and API names. 3) Payload Loading: The main function attempts to read an encrypted payload or configuration from a local file named 'access.log'. 4) Persistence and Execution: The code manipulates system services (referencing 'httpsvc' and 'ServiceD'), uses ExpandEnvironmentStringsA to target system directories, and dynamically resolves APIs to execute extracted code or drop additional components. Relevant IOCs include the file path suffix '\access.log' and the hardcoded magic value 0x12345678 used for payload verification.
